        heading: 'Floor Plan Financing and Inventory Management',
        content: "Floor plan financing — credit facilities provided by manufacturers or specialist agricultural finance companies to fund dealer inventory — is the primary working capital tool for EU agricultural equipment dealers. Floor plan facilities enable dealers to stock demonstration and display machines, take trade-ins, and maintain ready-for-delivery inventory without tying up equity capital.\n\nFloor plan terms typically provide interest-free periods of 60–180 days on new machine inventory, after which interest charges apply. Managing inventory turn within interest-free periods is a critical profitability discipline — machines that age beyond the free period accumulate finance charges that erode deal margin.\n\nUsed equipment trade-in management presents greater cash flow risk than new machine inventory. Used machines lack manufacturer floor plan support (or have limited facilities), carry higher depreciation risk, and require reconditioning investment before resale. Dealers with excessive used inventory — particularly aged stock beyond 12 months — face write-down risk and cash capital tied up in depreciating assets.\n\nInventory turn rate benchmarks for EU agricultural equipment dealers: new whole goods should turn 3–5x annually; used whole goods 4–6x; parts inventory 3–4x. Dealers with significantly lower turn rates are carrying excess inventory that consumes working capital without proportional revenue generation."
