        level: 2,
        heading: 'Working Capital Planning and Facility Management',
        content: "EU agricultural equipment dealers require working capital facilities structured for their specific cash flow dynamics. Seasonal overdraft facilities that increase limits during peak inventory periods and reduce during lower-activity months match the natural business cycle better than flat annual limits.\n\nCash flow forecasting for dealers should model: expected whole goods sales by month (informed by order pipeline and historical seasonality), trade-in acquisition and resale timing, floor plan drawdown and repayment, parts and service revenue forecasts, and manufacturer bonus and incentive payment timing (often paid quarterly or annually based on sales targets).\n\nManufacturer incentive programmes — volume bonuses, demonstration subsidies, marketing contribution funds, and target achievement payments — represent significant income for EU dealers but are often paid well after the qualifying period. Dealers should track accrued manufacturer incentives and factor them into cash flow planning while recognising the timing lag between earning and receipt.\n\nProperty and premises costs for EU agricultural equipment dealers are significant — workshop facilities, parts warehousing, display areas, and machinery storage require substantial footprint. Dealers in owned premises have different capital structures from leased operators; both must manage premises cost as a percentage of revenue to maintain overall profitability.\n\nDealer succession planning has cash flow implications. Many EU agricultural equipment dealerships are family businesses approaching generational transition. Management buyouts, family succession arrangements, or eventual sale to dealer groups all require long-term financial planning that affects current cash flow management priorities."
