        content: "Camera equipment, lighting, audio gear, and computing hardware represent significant capital investment for EU photography and videography businesses. A professional camera system (body, lenses, lighting) costs €5,000–€25,000; videography packages including cinema cameras, gimbals, audio, and lighting run €15,000–€50,000+; editing workstations €2,000–€5,000.\n\nEquipment depreciation is a real business cost that many creative professionals ignore in their pricing. Camera bodies depreciate significantly — losing 30–50% of value within 2–3 years as new models release. Lenses retain value better but still depreciate. Budgeting for equipment replacement by setting aside 15–20% of equipment value annually as a depreciation reserve ensures replacement funding is available when equipment reaches end of useful life.\n\nEquipment insurance — covering theft, accidental damage, and professional use — costs €500–€2,000 annually for comprehensive professional photography and videography cover. Uninsured equipment loss can be business-ending for sole practitioners who lack reserves to replace stolen or damaged kit.\n\nRenting versus owning specialist equipment provides flexibility for less frequently used items. Specialist cinema lenses, high-end lighting systems, and drone equipment that is used occasionally for specific projects are often more economically rented per-project than purchased outright. Purchase is justified when utilisation exceeds approximately 40 rental-equivalent days per year."
