        content: "EU photography and videography businesses should select a business structure that balances liability protection, tax efficiency, and administrative simplicity. Most EU member states offer sole trader registration (simplest administration, unlimited personal liability) and limited company formation (liability protection, potentially more tax-efficient above certain income thresholds).\n\nVAT registration thresholds vary by EU member state. Photographers below the threshold face a choice: voluntary registration enables VAT recovery on equipment and expenses but requires charging VAT on client invoices (potentially making services more expensive for non-VAT-registered clients). Above the threshold, registration is mandatory. B2B commercial photography clients can recover VAT charged, so the pricing impact is neutral; B2C clients (weddings, portraits) absorb VAT as a cost increase.\n\nExpense management discipline is critical for creative businesses where personal and business use of equipment, vehicles, and home workspace can blur. EU tax authorities in most member states allow proportional business use deductions for mixed-use assets and home office costs, but require reasonable documentation of business use proportion.\n\nPension provision for self-employed EU photographers and videographers deserves specific attention. The irregular income patterns of creative businesses make consistent pension contributions challenging, but the absence of employer pension contributions makes personal provision essential. Many EU member states offer tax-advantaged pension savings for self-employed individuals that provide immediate tax benefit alongside long-term retirement provision.\n\nProfessional indemnity insurance — covering claims arising from professional service delivery (missed deadlines, data loss, content disputes) — is increasingly expected by corporate clients and provides genuine risk protection for businesses where a single data loss (corrupted wedding photos, failed video delivery) could generate significant liability."
